    "body": "Yeah, there is definitely nuance here. In order to be a successful developer language for more than small uses, we need some way of separating concerns where it makes sense and doesn't obfuscate the program.\r\n\r\nMy suggestion using statements will be for two uses:\r\n* package imports from eth-pm:\r\n```python\r\nfrom zeppelin.token import ERC20\r\n\r\n# variable pointing to an ERC20-compatible token contract\r\nmy_token: ERC20\r\n...\r\n```\r\n* importing other local files as self-contained, composed types\r\n```python\r\nimport Boardmember\r\n\r\n# create a group of 5 Boardmembers, whose functionality is defined in './Boardmember.vy'\r\nboard: Boardmember[5]\r\n...\r\n```\r\n\r\nIn both cases, you will already have a full understanding of exactly what it is you are importing, so you are not going back and forth between files to understand what is going on. Interfaces are easy in this way (e.g. ERC20), and our model for composable object types will have to be flushed out for our v2 release.",
