    "body": "So... here's my take on these.\r\n\r\n**Imports and/or package support (ethpm)**\r\n\r\nImports... Not like this, please. Not generic imports. It defeats the whole point of Vyper. I see two specific points where imports are a valid use case:\r\n\r\n- Calling external contracts by its abi. The abi could be importable, so one doesn't need to craft calls by hand via keccak hashing.\r\n\r\n- Deploying new contracts from a factory contract. In order to make builds not-painful, we need a way to import the binary of child contracts, to deploy it from contract methods.\r\n\r\nSo... how about this? Vyper should never import Vyper files. We need specific imports to import ABIs and contract binaries. ABIs should be represented as types (classes), while binaries (or in general, strings) should be represented as constants for the programmer.\r\n\r\n**Including on-chain deployed libraries**\r\n\r\nNo. Just no. Not like this.\r\n\r\nWe really need to rethink libraries from the ground up. Libraries sound good, but are the number 1 security vulnerability of Ethereum. If Vyper gets on the messed up crap Solidity library bandwagon, I'll consider it officially dead to me.\r\n\r\nDeployed libraries are a good idea. But we need serious, serious, serious work on the concept, re-architecting it from the ground up, and coming up with a solution that is secure, reliable and auditable.\r\n\r\n**Struct classes**\r\n\r\nWhat is the use case where this would be good for anything other than writing unsafe code?\r\n\r\n**Composable Types \"Widgets\"**\r\n\r\nI don't understand what the author meant by this sequence of words. ;)\r\n\r\n**Library Support**\r\n\r\nPlease don't.",
