    "body": "Here's a quick thought train about what the philosophy of Vyper should be on code reuse. If more of you agree with me, or find it useful, it could be elevated to a guideline that should inform decisions on requests and questions such as imports, libraries and similar things.\r\n\r\nSo...\r\n\r\n**Daniel's Ethereum smart contract ars poetica**\r\n\r\nEthereum smart contracts run on a very limited platform (the EVM), that in many of its limitations, is comparable to a punchcard computer from the 70s. For this reason, using modern programming paradigms useful on low-security and high capacity (virtually unlimited) systems will yield all of the drawbacks, but none or few of the benefits of these approaches.\r\n\r\nSo an Ethereum smart contract should follow the traditional Unix application philosophy. A single contract should do a single, very narrowly defined thing. Complex behaviors should emerge from the interplay of multiple separate, independent contracts, as opposed to through one complex contract.\r\n\r\nFor this reason, in-contract code composition is not only undesirable from a security standpoint, it is useless from a best practice development standpoint. We need to provide tools that make it easy for developers to write contracts that can easily interact with other contracts. An existing, successful example of this paradigm is the built-in cryptographic precompiles in Ethereum, accessible from smart contracts as separate contracts through an ABI and fixed address.",
