    "created_at": "2018-05-31T13:51:08Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-05-31T13:51:08Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Personally, my primary use of packages would be for standard interfaces like `ERC20` and for collecting my compiled smart contract system into one file for testing or front end use. Library support (and libraries in general) I am much less convinced on their overall utility, but @pipermerriam has been convincing me.\r\n\r\nI think ultimately, you cannot have a single 1000+ line contract and have it remain understandable without significant effort. Breaking down concepts and composing them where they make sense can make it more readable and safer because the compiler takes care of linking things together. Ultimately there is a limit on complexity of a contract, so most applications will end up defining multiple contracts anyways.\r\n\r\nI absolutely agree with you on the Unix philosophy, \"do one thing and do it well\" should definitely be a principle Vyper contracts adhere to.",
