    "created_at": "2018-05-31T14:52:15Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-05-31T14:57:54Z",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "body": "ERC20 is not a package, it's an ABI. We need the ability to import ABIs, not \"packages\".\r\n\r\nAs for collecting the smart contract system into one file, I'm not quite sure what you mean. Something like a Truffle migration? That would be a build and deployment toolchain question, which we should clearly demarcate from the compiler.\r\n\r\nThere's the compiler, which is Vyper specific, and then we could work on toolchain stuff that should be language agnostic, operating on ABIs and EVM binaries.\r\n\r\n> Library support (and libraries in general) I am much less convinced on their overall utility, but @pipermerriam has been convincing me\r\n\r\nOn-chain libraries are useful, but very dangerous. I am extremely against having this functionality as a language citizen. Instead, well-known contracts deployed on the chain could be used for reusable logic, similarly to the EVM precompiles. (Ie. you explicitly call them as contracts.)\r\n\r\nAs for delegatecall'ing them, that's inherently unsafe. I guess we need the ability to do delegatecalls, but let's not make it too self-evident or enticing... And definitely don't make it look like \"the right way\" or even \"**a** right way\" for purposes of code reuse. I still remember the Parity multisig... ;)\r\n\r\nLocal (build-time) libraries would kill auditability. We'd get the similar library hell that Javascript has. Only on Ethereum it's so much worse. \"Well I have this include that has publicly available source, and it looks safe... but back when I compiled the contract, the one I compiled it with had a backdoor, so your money is now mine.\"\r\n\r\nFor Ethereum contracts, copy-pasting code seems like a perfectly acceptable way. Later, we could have a developer ecosystem with shareable code snippets of common code to be included (maybe via an IDE)... but that's different from libraries.\r\n\r\nA Vyper standard library that is audited and proven to be safe could be a common ground between the requirements of security and developer friendliness.\r\n\r\n> I think ultimately, you cannot have a single 1000+ line contract and have it remain understandable\r\n\r\nI think you shouldn't have a 1000+ line contract, period. ;) (Likely deployment won't fit into block gas limit anyway.)",
